The NDAA for Fiscal Year 2013 passed the [[House Armed Services Committee]] 56-5 on May 10. The bill as reported to the House authorizes $554.2 billion in base [[The Pentagon|Pentagon]] spending and $88.5 billion for overseas contingency operations (OCO).<ref>{{cite web|last=Herb |first=Jeremy |url=http://thehill.com/blogs/defcon-hill/budget-appropriations/226651-house-committee-passes-643-billion-defense-bill |title=House panel moves $643B defense bill - The Hill's DEFCON Hill |publisher=Thehill.com |date=2012-05-10 |accessdate=2012-05-21}}</ref> The bill passed the full House on May 18 by a vote of 299-120.<ref>{{cite news|title=US House passes huge defense budget bill|url=http://www.thenews.com.pk/article-49816-US-lawmakers-pass-huge-defense-spending-bill|agency=Associated Press|publisher=The International News|accessdate=13 July 2012|date=19 July 2012}}</ref> The bill was approved by the Senate on December 4, 2012 by a vote of 98-0.<ref name="IndianCountry20121206">{{cite news|title=Senate Passes 2013 National Defense Authorization Act; Feinstein Amendment May Extend Indefinite Detention Power|url=http://indiancountrytodaymedianetwork.com/article/senate-passes-2013-national-defense-authorization-act-feinstein-amendment-may-extend|accessdate=29 December 2012|newspaper=Indian Country|date=6 December 2012|author=Gale Courey Toensing}}</ref> The U.S. House of Representatives and the Senate passed the Conference Report on the National Defense Authorization Act for Fiscal Year 2013 in December 2012. The House passed it on December 20, 2012 with a vote of 315 yeas to 107 noes; the Senate passed it on December 21, 2012 with a vote of 81 yeas to 14 noes.<ref>{{cite news|title=UPDATE: Congress passes National Defense Authorization Act for Fiscal Year 2013|url=http://www.guampdn.com/article/20121222/NEWS01/121222002/UPDATE-Congress-passes-National-Defense-Authorization-Act-Fiscal-Year-2013|accessdate=29 December 2012|newspaper=Pacific Daily News|date=22 December 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Sledge|first=Matt|title=NDAA Indefinite Detention Bill Passes Senate After Rand Paul Calls It An 'Abomination'|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/12/21/ndaa-indefinite-detention-bill-rand-paul_n_2347774.html|accessdate=20 July 2013|newspaper=The Huffington Post|date=21 December 2012}}</ref> President Barack Obama signed the 2013 National Defense Authorization Act<ref name="THP20130103" /> on January 2, 2013.<ref name="Lawfare20130102">{{cite web|last=Obama|first=Barack|title=Statement by the President on H.R. 4310|url=http://www.lawfareblog.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/2013ndaa.stm_.rel_.pdf.pdf|work=The White House Office of the Press Secretary|publisher=Lawfare Blog|accessdate=4 January 2013|date=2 January 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Obama|first=Barack|title=Statement by the {{sic|nolink=y|the}} President on H.R. 4310|url=http://www.whitehouse.gov/the-press-office/2013/01/03/statement-president-hr-4310|work=The White House Office of the Press Secretary|publisher=The White House Office of the Press Secretary|accessdate=4 January 2013|date=2 January 2013}}</ref>

The bill authorizes fiscal year 2013 appropriations for Department of Defense programs and military construction, Department of Energy national security programs, and Department of Transportation [[maritime security]] programs; authorizes recruitment and retention bonuses, special payments, and other authorities relating to the U.S. Armed Forces; and makes other modifications to national security, foreign affairs, and other related programs.<ref name="THP20130103">{{cite news|last=Reilly|first=Ryan J.|title=NDAA Signed Into Law By Obama Despite Guantanamo Veto Threat, Indefinite Detention Provisions|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/01/03/ndaa-obama-indefinite-detention_n_2402601.html|accessdate=4 January 2013|newspaper=The Huffington Post|date=4 January 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Carney|first=Jay|title=Statement by the Press Secretary on H.R. 4310|url=http://www.whitehouse.gov/the-press-office/2013/01/03/statement-press-secretary-hr-4310|work=The White House Office of the Press Secretary|publisher=The White House Office of the Press Secretary|accessdate=4 January 2013|date=2 January 2012}}</ref> The enacted act sets the U.S. Armed Forces' budget for the 2013 fiscal year to $633 billion.<ref name="THP20130103" /> It also contains a prohibition on transferring Guantanamo detainees to the U.S<ref name="THP20130103" /> and also includes the Afghan Women and Girl's Security Promotion Act.<ref name="AI20130103">{{cite web|last=Gregory|first=Carl|title=Amnesty International Condemns Guantanamo Transfer Restrictions in the 2013 National Defense Authorization Act|url=http://www.amnestyusa.org/news/press-releases/amnesty-international-condemns-guantanamo-transfer-restrictions-in-the-2013-national-defense-authori|publisher=Amnesty International|accessdate=5 January 2013|date=3 January 2013}}</ref>

In his signing statement to the Act Obama stated "Even though I support the vast majority of the provisions contained in [NDAA] I do not agree with them all. [...] Though I continue to oppose certain sections of the Act, the need to renew critical defense authorities and funding was too great to ignore."<ref name="Lawfare20130102" /><ref name="Politico20130103" /> Among these provisions are those that effectively thwart Obama's efforts to close [[Guantanamo Bay detention camp]] and give military members the right to refuse to take certain actions that violate their conscience.<ref name="Politico20130103">{{cite web|last=Gerstein|first=Josh|title=Obama signs defense bill, notes regrets|url=http://www.politico.com/blogs/under-the-radar/2013/01/obama-signs-defense-bill-notes-regrets-153222.html|publisher=Politico|accessdate=4 January 2013|date=3 January 2013}}</ref> The president was criticized by civil rights and human rights organizations for his signing. American Civil Liberties Union Executive Director Anthony Romero said with respect to [[w:National Defense Authorization Act for Fiscal Year 2012#Indefinite detention without trial: Section 1021|the 2012 NDAA indefinite detention provisions]] and Obama's signature under the 2013 NDAA: "His signature means that indefinite detention without charge or trial, as well as the illegal military commissions, will be extended."<ref>{{cite web|title=Obama signs NDAA 2013 without objecting to indefinite detention of Americans|url=http://rt.com/usa/news/obama-ndaa-detention-president-288/|publisher=Russia Today|accessdate=5 January 2013|date=3 January 2013}}</ref> "This law makes it harder for the President to fulfill his promise to close the Guantanamo detention facility, perpetuating a grave injustice against the detainees held without charge or fair trial," said Frank Jannuzi, Deputy Executive Director of Amnesty International USA. "Solutions for ending human rights violations, not excuses, must be found."<ref name="AI20130103" />

===Feinstein-Lee Amendment===

The NDAA, an otherwise mundane annual bill that lays out the use of funds for the Department of Defense, has come under attack during the Obama administration for the introduction of a provision in 2012  that allows the military to detain United States citizens indefinitely without charge or trial for mere suspicions of ties to terrorism. Under the 2012 NDAA's Sec. 1021, U.S. President Obama did not agree to give the military the power to arrest and hold Americans without the writ of habeas corpus as he promised with that year's signing statement that his administration would not abuse that privilege.<ref>{{cite web|title=Obama signs NDAA 2013 without objecting to indefinite detention of Americans|url=http://rt.com/usa/news/obama-ndaa-detention-president-288/|work=Russia Today|publisher=Russia Today|accessdate=24 January 2013|date=3 January 2013}}</ref>

On December 4, 2012, the [[United States Senate|U.S. Senate]] unanimously passed the bill 98-0<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.senate.gov/legislative/LIS/roll_call_lists/roll_call_vote_cfm.cfm?congress=112&session=2&vote=00221 |title=U.S. Senate: Legislation & Records Home > Votes > Roll Call Vote |publisher=Senate.gov |date=2009-03-26 |accessdate=2012-12-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://thomas.loc.gov/cgi-bin/query/z?c112:S.3254: |title=Bill Text - 112th Congress (2011-2012) - THOMAS (Library of Congress) |publisher=Thomas.loc.gov |date= |accessdate=2012-12-06}}</ref> and added in Section 1033 the Feinstein-Lee NDAA Amendment<ref name="MJ20121130">{{cite web|last=Serwer|first=Jones|title=Will Congress End Indefinite Detention of Americans?|url=https://www.motherjones.com/mojo/2012/11/congress-indefinite-detention-ndaa|publisher=[[Mother Jones (magazine)|Mother Jones]]|accessdate=15 December 2012|date=29 November 2012}}</ref> which states: "An authorization to use military force, a declaration of war, or any similar authority shall not authorize the detention without charge or trial of a citizen or lawful permanent resident of the United States apprehended in the United States, unless an Act of Congress expressly authorizes such detention."<ref>{{cite web|title=Bill Summary & Status 112th Congress (2011 - 2012) S.AMDT.3018|url=http://thomas.loc.gov/cgi-bin/bdquery/z?d112:SP3018:|publisher=[[GovTrack]]|accessdate=15 December 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Congressional Record 112th Congress (2011-2012) - Text of Amendments - (Senate - November 27, 2012)|url=http://thomas.loc.gov/cgi-bin/query/F?r112:1:./temp/~r112Cj7k1Z:e302102:|publisher=[[GovTrack]]|accessdate=15 December 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Feinstein|first=Dianne|title=Detention Amendment No. 3018|url=http://www.lawfareblog.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/11/DetentionAmendment.pdf|work=Dianne Feinstein|publisher=Lawfare Blog - Hard National Security Choices|accessdate=15 December 2012}}</ref> Civil liberties group are concerned with this amendment because they think anyone on American soil should be given a trial if accused of a crime, given that the U.S. Constitution protects "persons," rather than "citizens."<ref name="MJ20121130" /><ref>{{cite web|last=Anders|first=Chris|title=Don't Be Fooled by New NDAA Detention Amendment|url=https://www.aclu.org/blog/national-security/dont-be-fooled-new-ndaa-detention-amendment|publisher=American Civil Liberties Union|accessdate=20 December 2012|date=29 November 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Wolf|first=Naomi|title=Feinstein amendment doubles down on NDAA's assault on constitutional rights|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2012/dec/05/feinstein-amendment-ndaa-assault-constitutional-rights|accessdate=20 December 2012|newspaper=The Guardian|date=5 December 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Savage|first=Charlie|title=Senate Votes to Curb Indefinite Detention|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/12/01/us/politics/senate-votes-to-curb-indefinite-detentions.html|accessdate=20 December 2012|newspaper=The New York Times|date=30 November 2012}}</ref> The Feinstein-Lee amendment is "inconsistent with the constitutional principle that basic due process applies to everyone in the US," said American Civil Liberties Union (ACLU) legislative counsel Chris Anders. Anders was also worried that the amendment could be construed to actually imply that the U.S. government has the constitutional authority for indefinite detention without charge and trial.<ref name="MJ20121130" /> "Moreover, we are very concerned that the Feinstein amendment implicitly authorizes domestic military detention. By seeking to protect only United States citizens and legal permanent residents, the amendment could be read to imply that indefinite military detention of any other persons apprehended within the United States was authorized in 2001 and was lawful," the ACLU wrote, referring to the Authorization for Use of Military Force, the founding document of the "war on terror" that was passed the week after the 9/11 attacks. "In addition, the clause 'unless an Act of Congress expressly authorizes such detention' could be read to imply that there are no constitutional obstacles to Congress enacting a statute that would authorize the domestic military detention of any person in the United States," the ACLU wrote.<ref name="IndianCountry20121206" />

A Congressional conference committee tasked with merging the House and Senate versions of the 2013 National Defense Authorization Act (NDAA) decided on December 18, 2012 to drop the Feinstein-Lee provision, which would have explicitly barred the military from holding American citizens and permanent residents in indefinite detention without trial as terrorism suspects.<ref>{{cite web|last=Bell|first=Zachary|title=NDAA's indefinite detention without trial returns|url=http://www.salon.com/2012/12/19/ndaas_indefinite_detention_without_trial_returns/|publisher=salon.com|accessdate=20 December 2012|date=20 December 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Savage|first=Charlie|title=Congressional Negotiators Drop Ban on Indefinite Detention of Citizens, Aides Say|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/12/19/us/politics/congressional-committee-is-said-to-drop-ban-on-indefinite-detention-of-citizens.html?_r=0|accessdate=20 December 2012|newspaper=The New York Times|date=18 December 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Kelley|first=Michael|title=Lawyers Fighting NDAA Indefinite Detention Slam Congress' Latest Decision|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/lawyers-mad-about-feinstein-amendment-2012-12|publisher=Business Insider|accessdate=20 December 2012|date=19 December 2012}}</ref> There was no reason given for this.<ref name="Politico20121812">{{cite news|last=Gerstein|first=Josh|title=Conference committee drops ban on indefinite detention of Americans|url=http://www.politico.com/blogs/under-the-radar/2012/12/conference-committee-drops-ban-on-indefinite-detention-152352.html|accessdate=20 December 2012|newspaper=Politico|date=18 December 2012}}</ref> Instead, the following replacement provivison was added:

{{quote|Nothing in the Authorization for Use of Military Force (Public Law 107–40; 50 U.S.C. 1541) or the National Defense Authorization Act for Fiscal Year 2012 (Public Law 112–81) shall be construed to deny the availability of the writ of habeas corpus or to deny any Constitutional rights in a court ordained or established by or under Article III of the Constitution to any person inside the United States who would be entitled to the availability of such writ or to such rights in the absence of such laws.<ref name="THP20121218">{{cite news|last=McAUliff|first=Michael|title=NDAA Indefinite Detention Provision Mysteriously Stripped From Bill|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/12/18/ndaa-indefinite-detention_n_2326225.html|accessdate=20 December 2012|newspaper=The Huffington Post|date=18 December 2012}}</ref>}}

The Huffington Post noted that the replacement version appeared to do little, because the Supreme Court has already declared that the writ of habeas corpus, i.e. the constitutional requirement that someone be presented to a judge, applies to all people. This was echoed from the civil liberties groups. "This language doesn't do anything of substance," said Raha Wala, a lawyer in the law and national security program of Human Rights First. "It doesn't ban indefinite detention within the United States or change anything about existing law."<ref name="THP20121218" /> Chris Anders from the American Civil Liberties Union called the language on indefinite detention of Americans "completely meaningless" and added there's no doubt that habeas rights are available to anyone who's detained in the U.S.<ref name="Politico20121812" />

HJ Adams, a lawyer for the group of journalists and activists suing the U.S. government over the 2012 NDAA, explained that the above quoted provision gives U.S. citizens a right to go to civilian (i.e. [[Federal tribunals in the United States|Article III]]) court based on "any [applicable] constitutional rights," but since there are no rules in place to exercise this right, detained U.S. citizens currently have no way to gain access to lawyers, family or the court itself once they are detained within the military. Afran added that the new statute actually states that persons lawfully in the U.S. can be detained under the Authorization for the Use of Military Force [AUMF], while [[w:Hedges v. Obama|the original statute from the 2012 NDAA which he is fighting]] never went that far. Afran concluded: "Therefore, under the guise of supposedly adding protection to Americans, the new statute actually expands the AUMF to civilians in the U.S."<ref>{{cite web|last=Kelley|first=Michael|title=Actually, The Newest Version Of NDAA Makes It EASIER To Detain Citizens Indefinitely|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/ndaa-americans-indefinite-detention2012-11#ixzz2FVuWSoLd|publisher=Business Insider|accessdate=20 December 2012|date=29 November 2012}}</ref>

===Smith-Mundt Modernization Act of 2012===

The ''Smith-Mundt Modernization Act of 2012''<ref name="SMMAHR5736">{{cite web|last=Thornberry|first=Mac|title=The Smith-Mundt Modernization Act of 2012 (H.R. H. R. 5736)|url=http://www.gpo.gov/fdsys/pkg/BILLS-112hr5736ih/pdf/BILLS-112hr5736ih.pdf|publisher=[[GovTrack]]|accessdate=5 April 2014|date=10 May 2012}}</ref> was introduced by U.S. Congressman [[Mac Thornberry]] on May 10, 2012 in the House of Representatives.<ref name="SMMAHR5736" /> The bill purpose is "to authorize the domestic dissemination of information and material about the United States intended primarily for foreign audiences"<ref name="SMMAHR5736" /> The act was added to the 2013 NDAA bill as section of 1078 to amend certain passages of ''[[Smith-Mundt Act|Smith-Mundt Act of 1948]]'' and ''Foreign Relations Authorization Act of 1987''.<ref name=GT20121228 /> The ''Smith-Mundt Modernization Act of 2012'' passed Congress as part of the NDAA 2013 on December 28, 2012.<ref name=GT20121228>{{cite web|title=Text of H.R. 4310 (112th): National Defense Authorization Act for Fiscal Year 2013 (Passed Congress/Enrolled Bill version) - GovTrack.us|url=https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/112/hr4310/text|publisher=[[GovTrack]]|accessdate=5 April 2014}}</ref> Amendments made to the ''[[Smith-Mundt Act|Smith-Mundt Act of 1948]]'' and ''Foreign Relations Authorization Act of 1987'' allow for materials produced by the [[State Department]] and the [[Broadcasting Board of Governors]] (BBG) to be released within US borders.<ref>[https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/112/hr4310/text See National Defense Authorization Act for Fiscal Year 2013 (section 1078 (a)) at the GovTrack.us entry Text of H.R. 4310 (112th): National Defense Authorization Act for Fiscal Year 2013 (Passed Congress/Enrolled Bill version)]</ref><ref name="FP20130716">{{cite news|last=Hudson|first=John|title=U.S. Repeals Propaganda Ban, Spreads Government-Made News to Americans|url=http://thecable.foreignpolicy.com/posts/2013/07/12/us_backs_off_propaganda_ban_spreads_government_made_news_to_americans|accessdate=16 July 2013|newspaper=Foreign Policy|date=14 July 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Posel|first1=Susanne|title=How the NDAA Allows US Gov to Use Propaganda Against Americans|url=http://www.occupycorporatism.com/home/how-the-ndaa-allows-us-gov-to-use-propaganda-against-americans/|website=occupycorporatism.com|accessdate=9 June 2014|date=July 22, 2013}}</ref> U.S. Congressmen Adam Smith stated with the respect to the bill's purpose that al-Qaeda was infiltrating the Internet in order to promote anti-American sentiments and that with passage of the ''Smith-Mundt Modernization Act of 2012'' the US government would be able disseminate public diplomacy information by the State department to counter that in the Arabic language abroad.<ref name="RussiaTodaySource1">{{cite web|title=NDAA 2013: Congress approves domestic deceptive propaganda|url=http://rt.com/usa/news/propaganda-us-smith-amendment-903/|publisher=Russia Today|accessdate=4 January 2013|date=22 May 2012}}</ref><ref name="FP20130716"/>

Several news outlets reported that the 2013 NDAA overturned a 64-year ban on the domestic dissemination of propaganda (described as "public diplomacy information") produced for foreign audiences, effectively eliminating the distinction between foreign and domestic audiences.<ref>{{cite web|title=NDAA 2013: Congress approves domestic deceptive propaganda|url=http://rt.com/usa/propaganda-us-smith-amendment-903/|publisher=Russia Today|accessdate=5 April 2014|date=22 May 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=LeVine|first=Mark|title=The high price of 'dark fusion'|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/opinion/2012/06/20126294459762126.html|accessdate=5 April 2014|newspaper=AlJazeera|date=4 June 2012}}</ref><ref name="BFD20120518">{{cite news|last=Hastings|first=Michael|title=Congressmen Seek To Lift Propaganda Ban|url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/mhastings/congressmen-seek-to-lift-propaganda-ban|accessdate=5 April 2014|newspaper=BuzzFeed|date=18 May 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Kelley|first1=Michael B.|title=The NDAA Legalizes The Use Of Propaganda On The US Public|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/ndaa-legalizes-propaganda-2012-5#ixzz340YILjax|accessdate=9 June 2014|work=Business Insider|publisher=Business Insider|date=May 21, 2012}}</ref> The social news media site [[BuzzFeed]] for example quoted an unnamed source saying the ''Smith-Mundt Modernization Act of 2012'' would allow "U.S. propaganda intended to influence foreign audiences to be used on the domestic population."<ref name="BFD20120518" />

The Media and Outreach Coordinator for the U.S. State Department's Bureau of African Affairs, Gregory L. Garland, noted that the United States shoots itself in the foot by the release prohibition of materials produced by the State Department and the BBG within US borders and by preaching freedom of the press abroad while practicing censorship at home.<ref name="ADMarch2012">{{cite news|last=Garland|first=Gregory L.|title=Smith-Mundt: Censorship American Style?|url=http://www.unc.edu/depts/diplomat/item/2009/0103/ed/garland_smithmundt.html|accessdate=5 April 2014|newspaper=[[American Diplomacy]]|date=March 2009}}</ref> He argued against a complete repeal of the ''Smith-Mundt Act of 1948'' stating that the law "creates a statutory firewall between resources intended for foreign audiences and those used domestically.  Tear down that firewall, and it will be a matter of time before resources and personnel who focus on talking about America overseas are diverted in favor of domestic "public affairs," the short-term political imperative of any administration." An unnamed Pentagon official who was concerned about the 2012 law version stated: "It removes the protection for Americans. It removes oversight from the people who want to put out this information. There are no checks and balances. No one knows if the information is accurate, partially accurate, or entirely false."<ref name="BFD20120518" /> The monthly magazine ''The Atlantic'' echoed those concerns by pointing out to two USA Today journalists who became target of a smear and propaganda campaign after they reported that the U.S. military "information operations" program spent millions of U.S. dollars in marketing campaigns in Afghanistan and Iraq criticized as ineffective and poorly monitored.<ref name="FP20130716" /><ref>{{cite news|last=Korte|first=Gregory|title=Misinformation campaign targets USA Today reporter, editor|url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/news/washington/story/2012-04-19/vanden-brook-locker-propaganda/54419654/1|accessdate=5 April 2014|newspaper=USA Today|date=19 April 2012}}</ref> As it turned out one of firm leaders who executed the marketing campaigns in Iraq and Afghanistan admitted to be a part of the smear and propaganda campaign against the USA Today reporters.<ref>{{cite news|last=Cook|first=John|title=Propaganda Contractor Admits to Running Smear Campaign Against USA Today Reporters (Update)|url=http://gawker.com/5913166/propaganda-contractor-admits-to-running-smear-campaign-against-usa-today-reporters|accessdate=5 April 2014|date=24 May 2012|publisher=gawker.com}}</ref>

While there are concerns as the described above there are also advantages by repealing the release prohibition of material materials produced by the State Department and the BBG within US borders. Garland for example wrote that the provision banning domestic dissemination deprives the United States in a communication age with no frontiers the U.S. of its "most powerful tool of soft power: our ideals."<ref name="ADMarch2012" />

