{{Lit-bio-book-stub}}

{{DISPLAYTITLE:''The Mercury Wonder Show''}}
[[File:Mercury-Wonder-Show-1943.jpg|thumb|right|300px|Advertising herald for ''The Mercury Wonder Show'' (August 1943)]]
'''''The Mercury Wonder Show for Service Men''''' was a 1943 magic-and-variety stage show by the [[Mercury Theatre]], produced by [[Orson Welles]] and [[Joseph Cotten]] as a morale-boosting entertainment for US soldiers in [[World War II]]. Directed by Welles, the show starred Welles ("Orson the Magnificent"), Cotten ("Jo-Jo the Great"), [[Agnes Moorehead]] ("[[Calliope]] Aggie") and [[Rita Hayworth]], whose part was later filled by [[Marlene Dietrich]]. [[Jean Gabin]] also worked on the show backstage, as a propman. The show ran to 150 minutes.

==Background==
[[File:Welles-Draft-1943.jpg|thumb|left|upright|Orson Welles leaving his Army physical examination after being judged unfit for military service (May 6, 1943)]]
In early 1943, the two concurrent radio series (''[[Ceiling Unlimited]]'', ''[[Hello Americans]]'') that Orson Welles created for [[CBS Radio|CBS]] to support the war effort had ended. Filming also had wrapped on ''[[Jane Eyre (1943 film)|Jane Eyre]]'' and that fee, in addition to the income from his regular guest-star roles in radio, made it possible for Welles to fulfill a lifelong dream. He approached the War Assistance League of Southern California and proposed a show that evolved into a big-top spectacle, part [[circus]] and part [[magic (illusion)|magic show]]. He offered his services as magician and director,<ref name="Magic">Charvet, David, "Orson Welles and The Mercury Wonder Show". ''[[Magic (magazine)|Magic, An Independent Magazine for Magicians]]'', Volume 2 Number 12, August 1993</ref>{{Rp|40|date=June 2014}} and invested some $40,000 of his own money in an extravaganza he called ''The Mercury Wonder Show for Service Men''. Members of the U.S. armed forces were admitted free of charge, while the general public had to pay.<ref name="Genii"/>{{Rp|26|date=June 2014}} The show entertained more than 1,000 service members each night, and proceeds went to the War Assistance League, a charity for military service personnel.<ref name="Billboard"/>

"It was just like a circus — I would have adored it if I'd been a member of the audience, I know that," Welles later told filmmaker [[Peter Bogdanovich]].<ref name="TIOW"/>{{Rp|177|date=June 2014}}

The development of the show coincided with the resolution of Welles's [[Selective Service System|draft status]] in May 1943, when he was finally declared 4-F — unfit for military service — for a variety of medical reasons. "I felt guilty about the war," Welles told biographer Barbara Leaming. "I was guilt-ridden about my civilian status."<ref name="Leaming Hayworth">Leaming, Barbara, ''If This Was Happiness: A Biography of Rita Hayworth''. New York: Viking, 1989 {{ISBN|0-670-81978-6}}</ref>{{Rp|86|date=June 2014}} He had been publicly hounded about his patriotism since ''[[Citizen Kane]]'', when the Hearst press began persistent inquiries about why Welles had not been drafted.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://framework.latimes.com/2011/09/28/orson-welles-rejected-by-army/ |title=Orson Welles Rejected by Army (May 6, 1943) |publisher=''[[Los Angeles Times]]'', September 28, 2011 |accessdate=2014-06-08}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wellesnet.com/?p=6392 |title=70 years ago: Orson Welles’ patriotism, military service made headlines |publisher=Wellesnet, May 3, 2013 |accessdate=2014-06-08}}</ref><ref name="McBride">[[Joseph McBride (writer)|McBride, Joseph]], ''What Ever Happened to Orson Welles? A Portrait of an Independent Career''. Lexington, Kentucky: [[University Press of Kentucky]], 2006, {{ISBN|0-8131-2410-7}}</ref>{{Rp|66–67|June 2014}}

Welles's fascination with illusion dated back to childhood; [[Harry Houdini]] gave him his first lessons in magic.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wellesnet.com/sketchbook4.htm |title=Orson Welles Sketch Book Transcripts, Episode 4  |publisher=''[[Orson Welles' Sketch Book]]'' at Wellesnet: The Orson Welles Web Resource |accessdate=2014-06-08}}</ref> His 1941 debut at the [[California State Fair]] (assisted by [[Dolores del Río]]) was a hit and, as "The Ace", he continued practicing his performance skills at vaudeville theaters and army camps. By 1943 Welles had developed a two-hour magic show.<ref name="Genii"/>{{Rp|26|date=June 2014}}

==Rehearsal and previews==
[[File:Mercury-Wonder-Show-Welles-Cotten.jpg|thumb|left|300px|George (Shorty) Chirello, [[Joseph Cotten]], Eleanor Counts and [[Orson Welles]]<ref name="Look"/>{{Rp|58}}]]
The show's name was a nod to [[Howard Thurston]]'s ''The Wonder Show of the Universe''. Welles adapted at least five of Thurston's illusions for his own show, and adopted his use of showgirls as stage extras.<ref name="Whaley"/>{{Rp|162–163}}

For ''The Mercury Wonder Show'', Welles selected [[Rita Hayworth]], one of the most popular women in motion pictures, as his chief assistant.<ref name="Magic"/>{{Rp|40|date=June 2014}}<ref name="Genii"/>{{Rp|26|date=June 2014}} In April 1943 he began teaching illusions to Hayworth, who was then living with him.<ref name="Whaley"/>{{Rp|163}} The couple practiced the [[Metamorphosis (illusion)|Houdini Substitution Trunk]] routine in the 125-seat private theater of [[Bill Larsen]], a successful Los Angeles attorney and magician who operated Thayer's Studio of Magic.<ref name="Whaley"/>{{Rp|163}}

Other cast included co-producer Joseph Cotten and, in his stage debut as comedy assistant, Welles's chauffeur, George (Shorty) Chirello.<ref name="Whaley"/>{{Rp|165|date=June 2014}} Welles hired [[Keye Luke]] — an accomplished visual artist as well as an actor — to design culturally authentic scenery and graphics, in contrast to the fake-Oriental visuals typically seen in [[Western culture|Western]] magic shows.<ref name="Whaley"/>{{Rp|167|date=June 2014}}

The show was rehearsed for 17 weeks.<ref name="Magic"/>{{Rp|40|date=June 2014}} Welles leased the Playtime Theatre (later the Las Palmas Theatre), a 350-seat house in Hollywood. Welles initially planned a moderate-sized magic show, open only to service members, that would run six weeks at the theatre and then tour army camps.<ref name="Whaley">[http://www.lybrary.com/barton-whaley-m-191.html Whaley, Barton], ''Orson Welles: The Man Who Was Magic''. Lybrary.com, 2005, {{ASIN|B005HEHQ7E}}</ref>{{Rp|164–165|date=June 2014}} Welles and the cast rehearsed from 7 p.m. until 2 or 3 a.m.; back home, Welles would spend the rest of the night improving the magic act and working out new bits of business. He tested 18 different openings before he was satisfied.<ref name="Whaley"/>{{Rp|167}}

Previews began in June.<ref name="Leaming Hayworth"/>{{Rp|87|date=June 2014}} As the show came together Welles began calling it "the biggest magic show on earth", and the cast and crew grew to 31 people.<ref name="Whaley"/>{{Rp|164–165|date=June 2014}} Welles bought or commissioned $26,000 worth of props and put $14,000 into the tent, scenery, costumes and rental of circus equipment. He also rented an entire menagerie, from a canary to a lion. [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer]] donated the venue, a lot near the [[Hollywood Canteen]] on Cahuenga Boulevard.<ref name="Magic"/>{{Rp|40|date=June 2014}}

==Production==
